5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 296, L.D. 442, “An Act to Amend the
10 Automotive Repair Statute”
11 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
12 following:
13 'Sec. 1. 29-A MRSA §1810, sub-§6, as enacted by IB 2023, c. 3, §3, is repealed.
14 Sec. 2. 29-A MRSA §1810, sub-§6-A is enacted to read:
15 6-A. Telematics system; diagnostic and repair function. Not later than 24 months
16 after the effective date of this subsection, a manufacturer that enables its dealers or
17 designated motor vehicle repair facilities in the State to perform a diagnostic and repair
18 function on the manufacturer's motor vehicles sold in the State that use a telematics system
19 shall make available, on fair and reasonable terms, to an owner of the manufacturer's motor
20 vehicle that uses a telematics system or to an owner-authorized independent repair facility
21 of the owner's choosing the means to perform the diagnostic and repair function on the
22 motor vehicle in a manner commensurate to that offered by the manufacturer to its dealers
23 and designated motor vehicle repair facilities in the State, which must include the capability
24 to remotely perform the diagnostic and repair function if the manufacturer enables its
25 dealers and designated motor vehicle repair facilities in the State to remotely perform that
26 function.'
27 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
28 number to read consecutively.
29 SUMMARY
3300 This amendment, which is the minority report of the committee, replaces the bill, which
3311 is a concept draft. The amendment repeals the required equipment section of the
3322 automotive right to repair statute and replaces it with certain manufacturer requirements
3333 regarding the performance of a diagnostic and repair function on motor vehicles that use a
3344 telematics system by owners and independent repair facilities.
